commentBody:
@PI-7

I don't know, but I am going to guess 10, on the average, based on how often C comes up in regular usage.

I'm sure some of the super solvers have that fact at hand.

@Aaron Teasdale

Our bigger concern is Milton Friedman.  I'd take Karl Marx any day over the Pinochet lover.

If Marx is responsible for the abomination that was the Soviet Union, the Friedman is responsible for the abomination that was Chile under Pinochet.

@Joe Kahr

Wow!  If the rows are labeled from the top down starting with A, then you're right--the fourth row ends in "e".

Every theory seems to get more complicated than the one before it.

@Mike

Seek your way out.

(Pro techs shun that method.)

@Francis
I agree about so easy posts.  I solved the puzzle okay but even reading the explanations for the final answer I was dumbfounded.

However, I appreciate new approaches and I'm not all grumpy about it.  Just surprised that people found it so easy.  I would suspect that anyone who found it easy (who didn't just guess) does other puzzles like cryptic.

@john ezra

Amen as to the witches and gourds—and especially escape rooms. 

Or, should I say, so mote it be.

@Tzvee

Very fun and very easy to crack.  Heck, all you really needed was the X to guess the rest.

I didn't really get the E clue reasoning though.  That's on me.  One for the road.

@R.J. Smith

Exactly, yes.  Was expecting an escape animation of some kind.

So what's with the blank gray square then?

@R.J. Smith

Yesterday you complained about animated effects and rebuses (even though there weren't any on the day), and today you seem to be disappointed by the lack of special effects... 🤷

As a grump and curmudgeon myself I can appreciate a good complaint - but c'mon, be consistent!

@Patrick J.
I took 16 to be the 16th letter of the alphabet. That delayed me for a long time. 
L

@CB

I think that's the third or fourth theory so far, and it's as good as any.

Surprisingly, I would have thought there would have been an unassailable answer to what is a pretty fundamental question for this puzzle.

@zhousephine

Though I foundered a bit on it, and honestly have had a better time doing crosswords, I do have to say that the more I stand back and look at this puzzle, the more of a marvel it is.

Congratulations on a future classic!

@Francis

Amazing -- I love that you even spared a thought for the puzzle after solving! Selfishly, we made exactly the kind of puzzle that * I * love, which, of course, is not going to be everyone's favorite. It's been really fun reading through the comments, and I'm glad we've been able to bring some folks fun and joy and some other folks consternation. :D

@Cathy

The pangram is a happy accident! JANKY was a late change to the grid; I can't recall exactly what was there before, but I think one of us caught a dupe and so made some changes in that section.

As for the E, it is meant to be the last letter of RODEO DRIVE. Kevin and I did have a lengthy discussion about whether it would be better to have a famous road that also ended in E, so it was less ambiguous... and now I can't remember why we didn't go that route. 

(One last thing: our original clue for RODEO DRIVE was [Road paved with gold, metaphorically], to give the extra hint that you were at the correct ROAD, but that didn't make it past editing.)

@Jeff M

It doesn't look like that to me, at all, but you're probably right.  Even if so, there should have been animation of it opening.  :(

A little let-down after a fun and engaging (if too easy) puzzle.

@Dawn on the road

I, too, was expecting an animation at the end of the solve, maybe the black squares that make up the "door" exploding?  That would have justified the BREAKOUT STAR clue, as well.

Left me feeling mildly disappointed, but it was still a nice puzzle (or two puzzles).

@SP

Well I had TPs for a little while.

Does that count?  ;)

@CV

That may be the single most impressive thing to me.  Some said that there are an average of 8 or 9 (8 point something) C's in a typical Sunday crossword.

So there were some pretty severe restraints on the answers the constructors allowed themselves.

@Andrzej

I've never been to an Escape Room, but surely it can't be as unpleasant as going to those incredibly annoying Mazes that seemed to spring up everywhere a few years ago.
Why would anyone subject themselves to that???

@The X-Phile

The only mazes I know are hedgerow ones, and they been around for centuries. I don't mind one of those. I'm not sure what sort of maze you may mean. Maybe it was an American thing?

I have a really good relationship with my sister-in-law. We understand each other well. Or so I thought! Several years ago she wanted to invite us to an escape room!!! Ye gods... Fortunately she told us before she bought tickets.

@Betsy
Great comments
Go Dawgs!

@Rufo Sanchez 

If I should ever find myself in LA again I'll make sure to ask about the location of Rodeo Drive. I'll throw in the accent on the wrong syllable, and I'll be sure to use my best Georgia accent.

My last visit was basically the plot of a Tarantino movie, but fortunately I was one of the few involved who managed to escape unscathed.

@Brennan

I doubt you'd find a large plurality of Americans who truly believe in "inalienable" rights anymore.

At the moment, our rights seem quite alienable.

@Gemma

Does that mean that 5% of the time you're trapped forever?

I guess I don't really understand escape rooms.

@Linus

Ah.  

Well that makes sense.  Otherwise the escape room owners would have to figure out how to dispose of the people who failed.

@Matt

I'm 45 so probably not old school, but I feel the same as you about gimmicks like today's. I don't do a crossword to solve some riddle-based code for a single, unchecked entry - it's not the same as solving actual clues for words crossing with one another.

I'm ok with a rebus, I'm ok with hard clues, but this.... Meh.

@Andrzej

Agreed.  Plus, I spent far too long assuming my keyhole word was wrong before realizing I had a simple typo that I found via a quick scan.  
  That said, most of the time hard IS good and more satisfying.

@Holt

Here we need each *box* in the central entry to highlight a different specific entry.

Clicking on one *entry* to highlight another entry is available. But maybe not the refined functionality needed here? Don't know/recall one way or the other. My assumption is that the production team would have used the functionality if it were available. They're pros, after all.

@Rich in Atlanta

I would kindly ask that you remain on this planet!  We would all miss you too much if you go back home!! 

Although, to be honest, I don't know what the Wi-Fi situation is on your home planet and if you'd be able to still communicate with us here...  Probably just stay here and don't risk it.  ☺️

@HeathieJ

It'll still work.  The only hitch is the signal will take 250 years to get there, and 250 years to get back.

So make every word worth it!

@Marc A. Leaf

I think that may be the hard part for some (me included, maybe) to take, and that is that there are a lot of clever answers.  

Clever, but wrong.

@Joe P

You're at the END OF THE ROAD?

Yeah, I had to just stare at it for a while, too.

@Jacqui J
Great helping comments!  We were overthinking the italic clues, big time.
Merci!

@Ian
That's quite an interpretation, and a good one, at that. In past crosswords, the dash has indicated a continuation of an adjoining square, or simply a Freeform space. In this case, t-total could possibly be the emphasis on total, but that's my mind.
I was so excited to finally finish this puzzle, I didn't give it much thought.

@Ken

Look at the grid as a whole. The gray squares form the shackle on a padlock, with a keyhole in the padlock for 69D.

There certainly should have been an animated graphic at the end! A missed opportunity there.

@Ken

It seems to me that the gray squares represent the "bolt" of the padlock.
But it also seems to me that all these black and gray squares are wasted space in an otherwise enjoyable puzzle.

@Dave

😂😂😂

From one Cassandra to another, thanks for the laugh.

@Lsm

I envisioned the black squares that make up the "door" exploding across the surface of the puzzle, while the letters of BREAKOUT STAR flashed in multiple colors.

Perhaps it's better to leave the animations to our imaginations!

@SP

I enjoyed this puzzle, but viewing the comments of others as a "slap in the face"?  That might be being a bit too sensitive, imho.

I disagree with a lot of comments here, but the only ones that truly annoy me are the ones that criticize the hard work of the constructors.

@SP

The reason I like this puzzle is that after you solve the crossword puzzle, we get a second puzzle to find the key in the lock.  (I assume that's why you like it, too.)

But it doesn't surprise me in the least that there are many people who enjoy the first puzzle, but not the second.  And since they came here for a crossword puzzle, their dismay at having to solve this second puzzle in order to finish the first is understandably dismaying.

@SP
You are my favorite commenter on this blog, Dr P.

Hard to understand the vitriol.  Puzzles are for people who like figuring things out.

@Karl M

Why the needlessly mean comment? I don't, but a lot of people share their times. It's important to a lot of folks and isn't to others.  🤷‍♀️  Either way, this comment section is for all of us to share our thoughts. 

Yes, I suppose even mean ones if they don't cross a line, but I don't get the point.

@Karl M

Is that you, Professor Marx?  It was nice to see you in today's puzzle.

Did you get tenure at Cornell?

@George Krompacky

To me, getting blamed for something undeservedly is getting a *bum* rap.

(If Oikofuge were still with us, perhaps he would have already commented about bad vs. bum raps.)

@The X-Phile

I think this has more to do with how our minds work (under pressure?) than how deep the solvers knowledge is on any given topic. I have a harder time than I should dumping an answer, regardless of the likelihood it’s correct. I view it as going backwards. 

Eventually, it gets easier to change an answer than to keep it. Off we go, again.

@Francis
It would be very kind of you to consider curtailing such negativity for a while. I can appreciate your opinions, but you go a bit far with the anti-US comments. I get your angst, and I say this with the best of intent and civility.
Thank you

@Jerry

I don't know that I can do that.  

But I do appreciate your civility.

@TholosTB

That's true.  But there is also some genuine enthusiasm about it, as well.

I was mildly negative, but I definitely think it was more me than the puzzle.

@Dave
Strong agree. I thought that it would have been very helpful if we could have highlighted boxes in the escape word and the associated clue would turn yellow, too. Like when revealers and themers get highlighted together.  
(It was super frustrating doing this on my phone.)
